      "### Classification of Earth Orbits\n\nOrbits are selected based on the mission objective of the satellite:\n\n* **Low Earth Orbit (LEO)**: Altitude 160-2000 km. Ideal for earth observation, remote sensing, and space stations (e.g., International Space Station).\n* **Medium Earth Orbit (MEO)**: Altitude 2000 - 35,786 km. Commonly used for navigation satellite constellations (e.g., GPS, GLONASS, NavIC).\n* **Geostationary Orbit (GEO)**: Outer orbit at 35,786 km directly above the equator. Orbit period matches Earth's rotation (24 hours), so satellites appear stationary. Ideal for telecommunications and weather monitoring.\n* **Sun-Synchronous Orbit (SSO)**: Polar orbit in which satellite passes over any given point of the Earth's surface at the same local solar time. Used for imaging.",
