      "### Why the Industrial Revolution Began in Britain\n\nThe Industrial Revolution (mid-18th century) marked the transition from manual, agrarian production to machine-driven factory manufacturing.\n\n* **Capital Accumulation**: Wealth accumulated through global trade and colonial plunder provided the risk capital.\n* **Agricultural Revolution**: Enclosure movement consolidated landholdings, improved crop yields, and displaced small peasants, creating a large labor pool for urban factories.\n* **Natural Resources**: Abundant deposits of coal and iron ore located close to water transport networks.\n* **Scientific and Political Stability**: Britain enjoyed a stable constitutional monarchy (post-1688 Glorious Revolution) that protected property rights, alongside a culture of innovation (Steam engine, Spinning Jenny).",
      "### Global Consequences and Rise of Ideologies\n\nThe economic transformation reshaped global power structures:\n\n* **Socio-Economic Division**: Emergence of two main classes: Capitalists (bourgeoisie) who owned means of production, and industrial workers (proletariat) who sold labor under poor working conditions.\n* **Rise of Socialism**: Gaps between rich and poor led to critical ideologies. Karl Marx and Friedrich Engels wrote *The Communist Manifesto* (1848), advocating for a classless, stateless society.\n* **Imperialism**: Industrialized nations required raw materials (cotton, rubber) and markets for finished goods, accelerating the colonization of Asia and Africa."
